<ProjectLayout title="Documentation" activeSlug="documentation">
  <h2>Schematics</h2>
  <figure>
    <img src="/images/project/projschematic.png" alt="System schematic" />
    <figcaption>Schematics of the physical system.</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <p>
    The microphone connects to <code>PB0</code>, the ADC input of the MCU. The MCU connects to the FPGA
    via SPI, and the FPGA connects to the VGA display via a breakout cord. 270Ω resistors create a voltage
    divider with the VGA's internal 75Ω resistance, bringing 3.3V FPGA output down to ~0.7V required by each
    VGA color pin.
  </p>

  <h2>New Hardware</h2>

  <h3>Analog Microphone</h3>
  <p>
    We used the <a href="https://www.adafruit.com/product/1063" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MAX4466 from Adafruit</a>
    (2.4–5V supply, 20–20kHz detection range, 25×–125× adjustable gain). With GND, VCC, and OUT pins, it
    connects simply to the MCU's 3.3V breakout board. This let us use the ADC functionality not previously
    used in the course.
  </p>

  <h3>VGA Display</h3>
  <p>
    We used a 1024×600 pixel VGA display at 60Hz refresh rate. A
    <a href="https://www.adafruit.com/product/3125" target="_blank" rel="noopener">breakout cord</a>
    connects the FPGA to the VGA. The VGA allows use of FPGA primitives such as <code>PLL_B</code> for its
    clock — new from the previous labs. Full VGA control design is documented in the <a href="/project/fpga">FPGA page</a>.
  </p>

